{
  "title": "Multiplayer Game — Photon Unity",
  "desc": "A real-time multiplayer game I built with <span class=\"syn-fn\">Photon Unity Networking</span> featuring <span class=\"syn-str\">character selection</span>, abilities, <span class=\"syn-kw\">procedural maps</span>, 2D puzzles and <span class=\"syn-str\">networked synchronization</span>.",
  "aim": "Build a fully networked multiplayer game with real-time synchronization, character abilities and dynamic procedural content using Photon Unity Networking.",
  "about": "Developed a real-time multiplayer game using Photon Unity Networking (PUN2) as part of a module at Kingston University. Players join a shared server, select their own character prefab, and explore a procedurally updated map featuring flying islands, portals, dynamic object placement and timer-based 2D puzzles.\n\nMy contributions spanned almost every system in the game. I implemented networked player movement — switching from Rigidbody to CharacterController for better multiplayer responsiveness — and built the character selection system using RPCs to synchronize each player's chosen prefab across all clients. I programmed three special abilities: invisibility (disabling mesh renderers via RPC), steal (Raycast-based artifact theft from other players), and freeze (disabling an enemy's collider for 5 seconds across all clients).\n\nOn the map side I built randomized object placement that generates a different layout every session, portal teleportation, flying island spawn points and a water shader for visual polish. The 2D puzzle system dynamically selects puzzles from a tagged list, integrates with NPC characters that roam within a radius, and uses a shared IPuzzleComponent interface for consistent win, lose and reset logic across all puzzle types.",
  "takeaways": "Multiplayer is genuinely one of the hardest things to program — every system that works perfectly in single player breaks in unexpected ways the moment a second client joins. The biggest lesson was that ownership matters more than anything. Understanding which client owns which object, when to use RPCs versus PhotonView sync, and how to avoid race conditions taught me more about software architecture than any other project I have done.",
  "thanks": "Thanks to my teammates at Kingston University — designers, artists and fellow programmers — who contributed to the map design, puzzle content, character art and overall game vision. This was genuinely a team effort.",
  "highlights": [
    "Photon Unity Networking with PhotonView and RPC calls for real-time synchronization",
    "Character selection system syncing chosen prefabs across all clients via RPC",
    "CharacterController movement replacing Rigidbody for better multiplayer responsiveness",
    "Three networked abilities — invisibility, steal and freeze — all synced via RPC",
    "Randomized object placement generating a unique map layout every session",
    "Portal teleportation system and flying island spawn points",
    "2D puzzle system with timer, win/lose conditions and IPuzzleComponent interface",
    "NPC characters that roam within a radius and trigger puzzle popups on player proximity",
    "Unity Spline camera animation and water shader for visual polish"
  ],
  "tags": ["Unity", "C#", "Photon PUN2", "Multiplayer", "Networking", "RPCs", "Game AI", "Procedural Generation"],
  "image": null,
  "github": null,
  "live": null,
  "period": "2024",
  "category": "Game Dev / Multiplayer",
